<article id="migration-guide-article" class="px-4" style="display: none;">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Seasonal Bird Migration Guide</h1>
    
    <p class="mb-4">
      Bird migration is one of nature's most impressive phenomena. Each year, billions of birds travel thousands of miles between breeding and wintering grounds, navigating by stars, landmarks, Earth's magnetic field, and even their sense of smell.
    </p>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Understanding Migration Timing</h2>
    
    <p class="mb-4">
      Migration follows a predictable calendar in most regions, though exact timing can vary by species and weather conditions:
    </p>
    
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Spring Migration (March-May):</strong> Birds travel north to breeding grounds. Waterbirds and raptors often lead, followed by insect-eaters like warblers and flycatchers.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Fall Migration (August-November):</strong> Birds travel south to wintering grounds. Generally more spread out than spring migration, with shorebirds often starting in July.
      </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Migration Hotspots</h2>
    
    <p class="mb-4">
      Certain geographic features concentrate migrating birds, making these locations excellent for observation:
    </p>
    
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Coastlines:</strong> Many birds follow coastlines as navigational guides.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Ridges and Mountain Passes:</strong> Migrating raptors use thermal updrafts along ridges.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Major Waterways:</strong> Rivers provide navigation routes and rest stops.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Peninsulas and Land Bridges:</strong> Birds concentrate where land narrows.
      </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Tips for Observing Migration</h2>
    
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Time of Day:</strong> Dawn is best for songbirds; hawks often migrate mid-morning to afternoon.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Weather:</strong> Check forecasts for conditions that trigger migratory movements. Birds often move after cold fronts in fall and warm fronts in spring.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Night Migration:</strong> Many birds migrate at night. On clear nights in migration season, try watching the moon with binoculars to observe silhouettes passing by.
      </li>
    </ul>
    
    <p class="mt-8 mb-4">
      Migration is a vulnerable time for birds. You can help by keeping cats indoors during peak migration, turning off unnecessary lights at night to prevent disorientation, and supporting habitat conservation efforts along migratory routes.
    </p>
  </article>
  
