    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Bird Photography Fundamentals</h1>
    
    <p class="mb-4">
      Bird photography combines the thrill of bird watching with the creative outlet of photography. 
      Capturing these fast-moving subjects requires patience, preparation, and some specialized techniques.
    </p>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Essential Equipment</h2>
    
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Camera with Fast Autofocus:</strong> Birds move quickly, so a camera with good tracking capabilities is essential.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Telephoto Lens:</strong> A focal length of at least 300mm is recommended for most bird photography.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Tripod or Monopod:</strong> Helps stabilize longer lenses, especially in low light.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Extra Batteries and Memory Cards:</strong> You may spend hours in the field waiting for the perfect shot.
      </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Camera Settings for Bird Photography</h2>
    
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Shutter Speed:</strong> Use at least 1/1000 second for perched birds and 1/2000 or faster for birds in flight.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Aperture:</strong> A wide aperture (f/4 to f/5.6) helps isolate the bird from the background.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>ISO:</strong> Start with the lowest possible for conditions, but don't hesitate to increase it to maintain a fast shutter speed.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Drive Mode:</strong> Continuous shooting (burst mode) increases your chances of capturing the perfect moment.
      </li>
    </ul>
    
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Composition Tips</h2>
    
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>Rule of Thirds:</strong> Position the bird off-center for a more dynamic composition.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Background:</strong> Look for clean, uncluttered backgrounds that don't distract from your subject.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Eye Level:</strong> Whenever possible, photograph birds at eye level for a more intimate perspective.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Space for Movement:</strong> Leave room in the frame in the direction the bird is facing or moving.
      </li>
    </ul>
    
    <p class="mt-8 mb-4">
      Remember that ethical bird photography puts the welfare of the birds first. 
      Never disturb nesting birds or use calls/playback to attract birds, as this can disrupt their natural behavior.
    </p>
